raw_text:
Serena becomes world number two
 
 Serena Williams has moved up five places to second in the world rankings after her Australian Open win.
 
 Williams won her first Grand Slam title since 2003 with victory over Lindsay Davenport, the world number one. Men's champion Marat Safin remains fourth in the ATP rankings while beaten finalist Lleyton Hewitt replaces Andy Roddick as world number two. Roger Federer retains top spot, but Safin has overtaken Hewitt to become the new leader of the Champions Race. Alicia Molik, who lost a three-set thriller against Davenport in the quarter-finals, is in the women's top 10 for the first time in her career. Her rise means Australia have a player in the top 10 of the men's and women's rankings for the first time in 21 years. And Britain's Elena Baltacha, who qualified and then reached the third round, has risen to 120 in the world - a leap of 65 places and her highest ranking yet.

Serena Williams, known for her exceptional tennis skills and success on the international stage, has made history by becoming the world's second-highest ranked female player after her Australian Open triumph over Lindsay Davenport. The achievement marks an important milestone for the sport and highlights Serena's prowess in both women's and men's tennis.

As a result of her victory, Serena has moved up five spots to now hold second place in the world rankings. This ranking has also boosted her position in various tournaments and championships, including being placed in the top 10 for the first time in over two decades. This achievement is especially noteworthy given that Serena Williams has previously been ranked as high as number one in the world.

Williams' success on the court has also influenced her rise to a position of prominence in professional tennis. In addition to her victories, she has made significant contributions to the sport by advocating for equality and diversity within the game. Serena Williams continues to inspire both fans and fellow athletes alike through her passionate on-court presence and her outstanding achievements.
